docs.abstract: The politics and legality concerning the black body creates the show’s most moving episode yet.
docs.snippet: The politics and legality concerning the black body creates the show’s most moving episode yet.
docs.lead_paragraph: As a child I learned early and often the value of the black body in American culture. Black music, style, cuisine and literature have great worth both financially and artistically. But the black people that create these works are often treated with little humanity, a fact inadvertently highlighted by “La La Land,” with its treatment of jazz and near lack of black characters.

docs.abstract: The murder of a black man in New York reminds a Baltimore neighborhood of its own complicated racial history.
docs.snippet: The murder of a black man in New York reminds a Baltimore neighborhood of its own complicated racial history.
docs.lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — Under a gloomy sky, a crowd of a few dozen people assembled in the yard outside a stone church, a mostly white group who carried posters and wore T-shirts with messages like “Black Lives Matter,” “Stay Woke” and, simply, “BMORE Kind.” They had come on a Saturday evening to mourn a man they did not know, killed some 200 miles from here.

headline.main: Baltimoreans Mourn a Man Said to Have Been Killed by Their Neighbor

docs.abstract: Suggested reading from critics and editors at The New York Times.
docs.snippet: Suggested reading from critics and editors at The New York Times.
docs.lead_paragraph: This week, we’ve got a number of books on our list that are certain to get people talking. Cordelia Fine’s latest, “Testosterone Rex,” addresses head on some of the sexism that poses as neuroscience. Barry Friedman’s important new book, “Unwarranted,” takes on the volatile question of how to address abusive policing. And Angie Thomas’s “The Hate U Give” offers teenage readers a way to look at the Black Lives Matter movement. For sheer fun and entertainment? I recommend Bill Schutt’s “Cannibalism.” As readers will discover, that’s not as strange as it sounds. Bon appetit.

docs.abstract: The Ascend Public Charter Schools network tries doing away with unforgiving disciplinary codes.
docs.snippet: The Ascend Public Charter Schools network tries doing away with unforgiving disciplinary codes.
docs.lead_paragraph: Four years ago, while reporting on the difficulties of life in Brownsville, Brooklyn, one of the poorest neighborhoods in New York, I met a school administrator named Marsha Gadsden who worked for the Ascend Public Charter Schools network. Ms. Gadsden had grown up not far away, attended prep school on a scholarship and later went to Georgetown and Harvard, and she told me she worried about the unforgiving disciplinary codes used by her employer and so many urban charter schools around the country.

headline.main: A Brooklyn Charter School Looks Past ‘No Excuses’

docs.abstract: Beck, Kendrick Lamar and Tom Waits articulate the creative impulse.
docs.snippet: Beck, Kendrick Lamar and Tom Waits articulate the creative impulse.
docs.lead_paragraph: LATE LAST YEAR, a week before his final record was released and not quite four weeks before he died, Leonard Cohen held a press conference at the Canadian consulate in Los Angeles. Dapper in a dark suit, seeking support in his seat from a cane, the 82-year-old fielded questions. With a wit and candor and gentleness and wisdom that felt extraterrestrial, he spoke as though he’d traveled here from a civilization more advanced than our own to offer us a few gifts that could ensure the survival of our species. Near the end, there was a kind of apotheosis. A Japanese reporter asked Cohen about one of the lyrics from the new record’s title song, “You Want It Darker,” in which Cohen sing-speaks, “Hineni, hineni, I’m ready my Lord.”

docs.abstract: Maia’s divided loyalties control the future of Reddick, Boseman & Kolstad.
docs.snippet: Maia’s divided loyalties control the future of Reddick, Boseman & Kolstad.
docs.lead_paragraph: Familial bonds are often the trickiest ones to navigate. But as Maia learns, family need not be made up of one’s actual relations. This week’s episode of “The Good Fight” is full of clever twists and scintillating reveals, all of which work to break down Maia’s illusions about the privileged life her parents have swaddled her in. On one hand, this finally integrates her more fully within the culture of her new firm, which she has felt disconnected from despite the fact that her presence has been a disruptive one. On the other hand, there is something disturbing about the way Mike Kresteva’s witch hunt against Reddick, Boseman & Kolstad primarily circles around the white characters rather than the black lawyers who have built the firm from the ground up. That Barbara and Boseman — both finely acted characters — remain ciphers mars an otherwise stellar episode.
